<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>ADAM THIERER -- Heritage </TITLE>

<H3>ADAM THIERER</H3>
<HR>
<B>ALEX C. WALKER FELLOW IN ECONOMIC POLICY</B>
<P><IMG SRC="/heritage/staff/pics/thierer.jpe" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10>
<P>
Thierer examines how unnecessary regulations hurt Americas international competitiveness, with a particular focus on communications policy, electricity deregulation, antitrust law, and environmental risk regulation. 
<p>
Thierer's work on telecommunications has been featured in <i>The Wall Street Journal, The Washington Times, The Journal of Commerce, Communications Daily, Washington Telecom Week, Issues in Science and Technology, Consumers' Research</i>, and many other newspapers and newsletters. His proposals on universal service, interconnection policy, foreign ownership restrictions, Internet regulation, and wireless spectrum reform, have been credited as having a shaping influence on telecommunications legislation debated on Capitol Hill.
  <p>
Prior to joining The Heritage Foundation in March of 1992, Thierer spent time in London, England at the Adam Smith Institute where he worked on reform of the British legal system. Currently at Heritage, Thierer is conducting research on the effects of a comprehensive privatization program for publicly-held lands in the western United States.
  <p>
Thierer earned his B.A. in political science and journalism at Indiana University, and received his M.A. in international business management at the University of Maryland.
