<html>
<title>Denis Philip Doyle - Heritage</title>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<h3>Denis Philip Doyle</h3>
<hr>
<b>Senior Fellow In Education</b>
<p>
<img src="/heritage/staff/pics/doyle.gif" align=left hspace=10>
<p>
Denis Philip Doyle is The Heritage Foundation's Senior Fellow in Education. A nationally and internationally known education writer, analyst, and consultant, Doyle conducts research aimed at reforming America's educational system.
<p>
After earning his AB ('62) and MA ('64) in political theory at the University of California at Berkeley, he became a consultant to the California legislature, first as a program analyst, then as the architect of a series of education bills, including the <I>Ryan Act</I>, California's teacher licensing law.
<p>
In 1972, Doyle was named Assistant Director of the U.S. Office of Economic Opportunity in Washington, D.C., and later joined the National Institute of Education as Assistant Director where he oversaw the nation's two largest education demonstration projects, the <I>Education Voucher Project</I> and the <I>Experimental Schools Project</I>.  
<p>
He has been associated with "think tanks" since 1980 - The Brookings Institution, American Enterprise Institute, and the Hudson Institute - where he has written dozens of scholarly and popular articles for a wide variety of magazines, including <I>The Atlantic, The Public Interest, Change, Business Week, Education Week</I>, and <I>The Phi Delta Kappan</I>. He has also published more than 150 "op-ed's"
in the nation's most prestigious  newspapers: <I>The Washington Post, The Wall Street Journal, The Los Angeles Times</I>, and the <I>Baltimore Sun</I>. 
<p>
Doyle's books include <I>Investing in Our Children: Business and the Public Schools</I> (for CED), <I>Winning the Brain Race: A Bold Plan to Make Our Schools Competitive</I> (with David T. Kearns, then Xerox CEO) and <I>Reinventing Education: Entrepreneurship in America's Public Schools</I> (with Louis V. Gerstner, IBM CEO).
<p>
He has been a member of the <I>Phi Delta Kappa</I> editorial advisory board, the <I>RJR Nabisco Foundation Advisory Board</I>, the <I>US-Japan CULCON Advisory Board</I>, and was appointed by Secretary Alexander to the National Education Commission on Time and Learning.  
<p>
